Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

In this project we will analyse the dataset Tmbd movies and in particularly will be interesting in finding trends amoun the most popular movies with higher revenue and they differ from the movies with less revenue. The dataset contents the columns below:

    ID: Movie ID  
    Popularity: Popularity score  
    Budget: Amount spent to make the movie  
    Revenue: Amount realized from the movie  
    original title: Movie title  
    Cast: Actors & Actresses in the movie  
    Homepage: Movie website  
    Director: Director(s) of the movie  
    Tagline: Catchphrase(s)/slogan of the movie  
    keywords: Words associated with a movie  
    Overview: Movie Summary  
    Runtime: length of a movie  
    Genres: Category  
    Production companies: Companies that produced the movie  
    Release date: Date movie was released  
    Vote count:  
    Vote average:  
    Release year: year movie was released  
    Budget adj: Budget In terms of 2010 dollars  
    Revenue adj: Revenue in terms of 2010 dollars

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  • Movies with highest popularity?
  • Movies with highest budget?
  • Movies with highest revenue?
  • Movies with highest profit?
  • How does the popularity affect to the revenue?
  • How does the budget affect to the revenue?
  • How does the rating affect to the revenue?
  • Which Gender generate the most budget?
  • Does the director affect to the popularity?
  • Which Genre generate the most budget?
  • Does the Genre affect to the popularity?
  • Busiest time of the year to release a movie

Function to clean the revenue and budget¶

In [144]:
def clean_data(df):
    '''
    INPUT
    df - pandas dataframe 
    
    OUTPUT
    X - A matrix holding all of the variables you want to consider when predicting the response
    there are 1 step to clean the data:   
    1. revenue and budget in X, fill the column with the mean value of the column for the zero values.
    '''    
        # Fill numeric columns with the mean
    df[['revenue', 'budget']] = df[['revenue', 'budget']].replace(0, np.NAN)     
    df[['revenue', 'budget']] = df[['revenue', 'budget']].fillna((df[['revenue', 'budget']].mean()))

    X=df      
    return X

Function to create dummy value in categorical variables¶

In [148]:
def dummy_cat(df, var):
    '''
    INPUT
    df - pandas dataframe 
    
    OUTPUT
    1. Create dummy columns for all the categorical variables in X, drop the original columns
    '''   
        
    df = pd.concat([df.drop(var, axis=1), pd.get_dummies(df[var])], axis=1)
    X=df      
    return X

-Split the data into explanatory and response variables
-Split the data into train and test (using seed of 42 and test_size of .30 as above)
-Instantiate the linear model using normalized data
-Fit the model on the training data
-Predict using the test data
-Compute a score for your model fit on all the data, and show how many rows you predicted for use
the tests to assure you completed the steps correctly.

Conclusions¶

The dataset contains 56 years of movies data, cutting across several genres.

From the dataset there are 10865 movies from different genres. 2453 movies are drama movies, 2319 are Comedy movies and 1590 Action movies. There are also 915 Horror movies, about 586 adventure and 491 Thriller movies.

Avatar generated the most revenue and the most profit overall. It also ranks 12th on the all time most popular movie. It premiered in 2009 and was the most popular movie that year.

The Warrior's Way has the highest budget moview. However it is not between the movies with highest profit. We assume that It's probably running loss.

The most popular movie is the Adventure movie released in 2015, titled Jurassic World. Also having an excellent revenue and profit record.

Genres as adventure, comedy, drama and animation genres have relatively higher correlation coefficient than other features with revenue.

Talking about popularity & profit, from the visualization above we can notice a strong positive correllation between revenue and budget this means that in most cases the higher the budget for a movie there's a probability that the movie would generate as much profit.

Don't you think this will affect profit? Well, looking at the other correllation matrix table and the scatter plot, we'd notice a positive correlation between profit and popularity. What this implies is that as people keep talking about a movie, recommending it and making the movie trend, the revenue less the budget increases and this is more money for the directors and every one concerned.

So, if you are looking for a movie director to generate a lot of revenue for you then Steven Spielberg is the man for you.

Christopher Nolan had a fair share of the recognition as he is the most popular movie director as gets the highest value in popularity 61.95.

Revenue is skewed to the left with most of its values clustered between 0 - 1 X 10^(9), on the other hand, budget is also skewed to the left with most of its values between 0 - 2.5 X 10^(8). Some movies seem to run at a loss as profit margin ranges between -0.5 - 1 X 10^(9).

Let's look at runtime and popularity. The correlation between runtime and popularity depicts a low positive correlation. It means that the popularity of a movie does not really depend on its length. As mentioned above there are other factors that greatly influence popularity based on this dataset.

The busiest time of the year to release a movie are the months of September and October.

We have tried to predict the revenue based on the quantitative variables in the dataset. We compare the actual revenue with the predicted revenue values. Overpredictions tend to be much worse than the underpredictions

Limitation¶

The final cost of making a movie was not given

Social media comments or ratings were not given

Details of the rating column was not given

Also, from the correlation matrix table, Id was correlated with release year with a strong positive correlation but the id was just used to number the movie and has nothing to do with it the release year. This shows that correlation at times does not necessarily imply causation.

Amount of people that streamed the movie was not given
